false assumptions. There is no such a thing as a “normal” menstrual cycle. In fact, menstrual cycles are incredibly variable and highly responsive to environmental and psychological stressors. Clancy takes up a host of timely issues surrounding menstruation, from bodily autonomy, menstrual hygiene, and the COVID-19 vaccine to the ways racism, sexism, and medical betrayal warp public perceptions of menstruation and erase it from public life.Offering a revelatory new perspective on one of the most captivating biological processes in the human body, Period will change the way you think about the past, present, and future of periods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminism. 0aHuman bodyxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman body-Political aspects. 0aMenstrual cyclexSocial aspects. 0aMenstrual cycle-Social aspects. 0aMenstruationxSocial aspects. 0aMenstruation-Social aspects. 0aWomen's rights. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  aBoys Who Bleed.  aDegendering Menstruation.  aKate Clancey.  aMaking Trans Menstruators Matter.  aNon‐Binary Identity.  aPeriod.  aPhenotypical development.  aPregnancy.  aQueer Period Activists.  aQueering Menstruation.  aQueering periods.  aThe Real Story of Menstruation.  aTrans.  aanthropology.  aanti-racism.  aassigned female.  abirth control.  abodily autonomy.  acultural history of menstruation.  aendometriosis.  aeugenic history of gynecology.  aeugenics.  aevolution.  afalse theories of menstruation.  afeminism.  afuture of periods.  agender.  ahealth.  ahistory of medicine.  ahistory of science.  ahuman biology.  ainternal reproductive organs.  amenstrual cycles.  amenstrual hygiene.  amenstruation.  amensus.  amonthly bleeding.  anonbinary.  apsychological stressors.  areproduction.  arep